00:37:56.880 --> 00:37:59.690
So I was wondering if you
have any insights around that,

00:37:59.690 --> 00:38:03.295
especially given your pipeline
into Harvard Nutrition?

00:38:03.295 --> 00:38:05.170
MOLLIE KATZEN: You mean
about a low oil diet?

00:38:05.170 --> 00:38:06.110
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:38:06.110 --> 00:38:10.040
In fact, there are people
who say no oil diet.

00:38:10.040 --> 00:38:14.050
But olive oil, a
lot of that, do you

00:38:14.050 --> 00:38:18.037
have any insights as to whether
there is good research about--?

00:38:18.037 --> 00:38:19.620
MOLLIE KATZEN: I
have to qualify first

00:38:19.620 --> 00:38:21.810
by saying I am not a
nutrition researcher nor am

00:38:21.810 --> 00:38:28.960
I a dietitian, so I just pilfer
information from those who are.

00:38:28.960 --> 00:38:32.400
It's my understanding that
oil is very heart healthy,

00:38:32.400 --> 00:38:35.560
that olive oil, that you
should go out of your way

00:38:35.560 --> 00:38:39.590
to include it in your diet
because it is, in fact, a heart

00:38:39.590 --> 00:38:40.990
protector.

00:38:40.990 --> 00:38:45.640
And nuts also-- not even just
nut oils but nuts, avocados,

00:38:45.640 --> 00:38:49.030
those kinds of oils are
very, very healthful.

00:38:49.030 --> 00:38:51.790
And I believe-- and I
will check with him--

00:38:51.790 --> 00:38:54.270
but I am pretty sure that Dr.
Walter Willett of the Harvard

00:38:54.270 --> 00:38:56.728
School of Public Health, who
is the head of their nutrition

00:38:56.728 --> 00:39:01.040
department, is up to a
good probably 30% or more

00:39:01.040 --> 00:39:02.630
of the calories per
day that he would

00:39:02.630 --> 00:39:05.840
like you to get from
olive oil alone.

00:39:05.840 --> 00:39:09.340
The model is called
The Mediterranean Diet,

00:39:09.340 --> 00:39:12.170
and it also includes fatty fish.

00:39:12.170 --> 00:39:16.830
It also includes one or two
drinks a day of alcohol.

00:39:16.830 --> 00:39:19.290
So for people who like
alcohol, that's a nice thing.

00:39:19.290 --> 00:39:22.760
So for the people I know
and the people who school me

00:39:22.760 --> 00:39:24.580
in these things, I
would say that I'm

00:39:24.580 --> 00:39:30.100
very pro healthy oil
but anti unhealthy oil.

00:39:30.100 --> 00:39:33.770
But it's a question of
the quality of the oil.

00:39:33.770 --> 00:39:37.350
It's not all fat is bad,
but look for the good oils.

00:39:37.350 --> 00:39:39.080
In fact, it really
makes no sense

00:39:39.080 --> 00:39:41.800
according to these researchers--
and I am totally convinced

00:39:41.800 --> 00:39:45.020
by them-- to, when you
see those labels on food

00:39:45.020 --> 00:39:47.790
and they tell you
calories from oil,

00:39:47.790 --> 00:39:53.490
percentage oil, grams
of fat-- meaningless.

00:39:53.490 --> 00:39:54.780
What does that say?

00:39:54.780 --> 00:39:57.220
What do you take home from that?

00:39:57.220 --> 00:40:00.400
It's all about quantities of
fat, which don't mean anything.

00:40:00.400 --> 00:40:03.440
It's not a different
kind of calorie.

00:40:03.440 --> 00:40:05.650
It's not necessarily
bad or good.

00:40:05.650 --> 00:40:08.380
You have to look
further and see what

00:40:08.380 --> 00:40:10.100
is the actual source of fat.

00:40:10.100 --> 00:40:13.490
But it is my understanding
that a good oil

00:40:13.490 --> 00:40:15.550
is a very healthful thing.

00:40:15.550 --> 00:40:19.390
The expression, the phrase,
essential fatty acids,

00:40:19.390 --> 00:40:21.020
the word essential is literal.

00:40:21.020 --> 00:40:22.970
Those are fatty acids
that your body needs,

00:40:22.970 --> 00:40:24.977
that your body
cannot manufacture.

00:40:24.977 --> 00:40:26.060
So you need to take it in.

00:40:26.060 --> 00:40:28.720
You need to ingest it.

00:40:28.720 --> 00:40:30.650
AUDIENCE: Quick question
on pots and pans

00:40:30.650 --> 00:40:32.700
that are used in
cooking-- is there

00:40:32.700 --> 00:40:35.930
a difference between, say,
cooking in a non-stick pot

00:40:35.930 --> 00:40:38.920
or pan versus an iron
skillet, because I've

00:40:38.920 --> 00:40:41.410
been led to believe
that they do make

00:40:41.410 --> 00:40:43.290
a difference in the
flavor of the food?

00:40:43.290 --> 00:40:44.360
MOLLIE KATZEN: What's
your experience?

00:40:44.360 --> 00:40:46.080
What kind of difference
do they make?

00:40:46.080 --> 00:40:47.090
AUDIENCE: Well I just wondered.

00:40:47.090 --> 00:40:47.839
I don't cook much.

00:40:47.839 --> 00:40:48.900
I just hear about it.

00:40:48.900 --> 00:40:50.754
And I'm planning to
buy some pots and pans,

00:40:50.754 --> 00:40:52.545
so I thought your
feedback would be useful.

00:40:52.545 --> 00:40:55.330
MOLLIE KATZEN: Yeah, I do have
an opinion on it, just the way

00:40:55.330 --> 00:41:00.010
I feel about cooking and the
way a pot or pan feels to me.

00:41:00.010 --> 00:41:02.250
I want it to be as
heavy as possible,

00:41:02.250 --> 00:41:05.370
and I go for horizontal
cooking as much as I can.

00:41:05.370 --> 00:41:07.037
It's interesting.

00:41:07.037 --> 00:41:09.370
I could give a whole other
talk about how my cooking has

00:41:09.370 --> 00:41:13.250
changed, and one of the ways
is the shape of my cooking used

00:41:13.250 --> 00:41:15.410
to be more vertical, and
now it's more horizontal--

00:41:15.410 --> 00:41:20.210
horizontal meaning that
every tidbit in the pan

00:41:20.210 --> 00:41:23.460
gets its own place in
the sun, so to speak.

00:41:23.460 --> 00:41:26.570
Contact with the surface,
with the heating surface,

00:41:26.570 --> 00:41:29.310
is in itself a way of
flavor being imparted

00:41:29.310 --> 00:41:33.324
because that cooking
surface, depending

00:41:33.324 --> 00:41:35.740
on its proximity to the heat
and the intensity of the heat

00:41:35.740 --> 00:41:40.580
and the kind of oil,
is itself a seasoning.

00:41:40.580 --> 00:41:42.487
At that point, that's
the point where

00:41:42.487 --> 00:41:43.820
you can actually hear the sound.

00:41:43.820 --> 00:41:46.500
When you the sizzle of a
tidbit going into the pan,

00:41:46.500 --> 00:41:48.600
you hearing the
imparting of flavor.

00:41:48.600 --> 00:41:50.470
It's a beautiful thing.

00:41:50.470 --> 00:41:53.420
I don't like non-stick
pans because I'm

00:41:53.420 --> 00:41:56.750
suspicious of the materials
used in the coating, which

00:41:56.750 --> 00:41:57.750
can leach into the food.

00:41:57.750 --> 00:41:59.291
And they're chemical,
and they're not

00:41:59.291 --> 00:42:00.250
necessarily healthful.

00:42:00.250 --> 00:42:02.340
They can, in fact,
be unhealthful.

00:42:02.340 --> 00:42:05.755
This isn't completely-- I was
going to say it's not ironclad.

00:42:05.755 --> 00:42:06.410
[LAUGHTER]

00:42:06.410 --> 00:42:09.170
MOLLIE KATZEN: But it is
pretty much the rule of thumb

00:42:09.170 --> 00:42:11.050
is I would avoid coatings.

00:42:11.050 --> 00:42:12.980
So I like heavy.

00:42:12.980 --> 00:42:15.652
I love cast iron, and it's
also the least expensive.

00:42:15.652 --> 00:42:17.110
And for me, it's
the most nostalgia

00:42:17.110 --> 00:42:19.910
inducing because the
first cookware I ever

00:42:19.910 --> 00:42:22.050
had was cast iron.

00:42:22.050 --> 00:42:24.450
And it's a very honest cookware.

00:42:24.450 --> 00:42:28.256
And I like the fact you can
heat it really well and slowly.

00:42:28.256 --> 00:42:29.630
I'd much rather
have a pan that's

00:42:29.630 --> 00:42:32.110
been heated on a medium-low
flame for a longer

00:42:32.110 --> 00:42:36.390
period of time than flashing
something with a sudden burst.

00:42:36.390 --> 00:42:39.400
So I would go with
something-- anodized

00:42:39.400 --> 00:42:44.750
steel is a really nice,
heavy kind of cookware which

00:42:44.750 --> 00:42:46.330
I like a lot and
then the cast iron.

00:42:46.330 --> 00:42:49.410
But avoid anything
that's very lightweight--

00:42:49.410 --> 00:42:53.590
literally lightweight--
and that is coated.

00:42:53.590 --> 00:42:57.470
One way you can have a non-stick
situation without it being

00:42:57.470 --> 00:42:59.490
officially non-stick
is if you're

00:42:59.490 --> 00:43:01.700
patient with the
heating of the pan

00:43:01.700 --> 00:43:06.150
and make sure it gets very,
very hot and then add your oil.

00:43:06.150 --> 00:43:09.820
And then make sure the
oil itself gets very hot

00:43:09.820 --> 00:43:13.560
so that when the food finally
goes in, you hear the sizzle.

00:43:13.560 --> 00:43:15.030
Again, hearing the
sizzle tells you

00:43:15.030 --> 00:43:16.650
that it's probably
not going to stick.

00:43:16.650 --> 00:43:18.800
And then you have
a metal spatula

00:43:18.800 --> 00:43:20.730
with which you scrape
the food as it cooks.

00:43:20.730 --> 00:43:24.040
And you shake it, keep it
going, to keep it from sticking.

00:43:24.040 --> 00:43:25.650
You're the non-stick factor.

00:43:25.650 --> 00:43:28.870
Your cooking habit becomes
the non-stick factor.

00:43:28.870 --> 00:43:32.430
My recipes used to say, oh,
just cook the vegetable.

00:43:32.430 --> 00:43:34.074
It didn't even
say, heat the pan.

00:43:34.074 --> 00:43:35.490
I don't even
remember what I said.

00:43:35.490 --> 00:43:38.210
But now I very
specifically almost always

00:43:38.210 --> 00:43:42.860
have one clear instruction
first, pan on heat.

00:43:42.860 --> 00:43:45.700
Wait.

00:43:45.700 --> 00:43:48.000
Oil goes in.

00:43:48.000 --> 00:43:49.010
Wait.

00:43:49.010 --> 00:43:50.290
Swirl to coat.

00:43:50.290 --> 00:43:50.790
Wait.

00:43:50.790 --> 00:43:53.250
There's a lot of waiting.

00:43:53.250 --> 00:43:54.820
It's like a time
signature in music.

00:43:54.820 --> 00:43:56.204
There's a little rest.

00:43:56.204 --> 00:43:57.620
And then the food
goes in, and you

00:43:57.620 --> 00:44:01.840
hear the sound of it being
infused with flavor and with it

00:44:01.840 --> 00:44:04.665
becoming something that's
not going to stick.

00:44:04.665 --> 00:44:05.267
Did that help?

00:44:05.267 --> 00:44:06.600
AUDIENCE: Absolutely, thank you.

