had a lot to do with
opening the package.

00:46:50.029 --> 00:46:51.570
First you go to one
end and you open.

00:46:51.570 --> 00:46:52.220
You tear it.

00:46:52.220 --> 00:46:54.386
And then if it doesn't open,
you take a little knife

00:46:54.386 --> 00:46:55.510
and cut it open.

00:46:55.510 --> 00:46:58.000
But it was all about getting
it out of the package.

00:46:58.000 --> 00:47:00.150
And then you add water
and put it on heat.

00:47:00.150 --> 00:47:03.950
And then when the corners fall
off and it's no longer square,

00:47:03.950 --> 00:47:04.834
serve.

00:47:04.834 --> 00:47:05.750
That was my early one.

00:47:05.750 --> 00:47:07.317
But now it's about the knife.

00:47:07.317 --> 00:47:09.400
Now it's about, you get
the fresh vegetables home.

00:47:09.400 --> 00:47:13.780
And for a lot of
people, I believe

00:47:13.780 --> 00:47:15.880
the barrier to cooking
more vegetables

00:47:15.880 --> 00:47:18.977
is a little bit of uneasiness
about the knife, which

00:47:18.977 --> 00:47:20.060
is a very essential thing.

00:47:20.060 --> 00:47:21.970
I call it the knife block.

00:47:21.970 --> 00:47:27.710
And again, we talk about
the line in the sand,

00:47:27.710 --> 00:47:29.300
before and after.

00:47:29.300 --> 00:47:31.940
There is before you
bond with your knife.

00:47:31.940 --> 00:47:34.320
And then there is
post-bonding with your knife.

00:47:34.320 --> 00:47:35.620
It's a whole different world.

00:47:35.620 --> 00:47:37.390
When you find the
knife of your dreams,

00:47:37.390 --> 00:47:40.000
it's like finding
a relationship.

00:47:40.000 --> 00:47:43.500
And there's no one knife
that's right for everyone.

00:47:43.500 --> 00:47:45.690
But there is a knife
that's right for you.

00:47:45.690 --> 00:47:50.190
And it feels good in your hand,
and it's got a straight blade.

00:47:50.190 --> 00:47:54.600
It can be a 6, 8, 10-inch
blade, but it feels good to you.

00:47:54.600 --> 00:47:56.490
And you keep it very,
very, very sharp.

00:47:56.490 --> 00:47:59.250
You have it professionally
sharpened once or twice a year.

00:47:59.250 --> 00:48:02.000
And it is so exciting
to try to cut something

00:48:02.000 --> 00:48:04.370
with a sharp knife
for the first time.

00:48:04.370 --> 00:48:06.550
It heads toward an
onion or an apple,

00:48:06.550 --> 00:48:11.630
and with almost no pressure
from you, it grabs in.

00:48:11.630 --> 00:48:14.310
It's a clean slice.

00:48:14.310 --> 00:48:16.300
I'm so into sound
effects, so you

00:48:16.300 --> 00:48:18.470
can hear this little whoosh.

00:48:18.470 --> 00:48:21.400
And lo and behold, you
have a clean, perfect slice

00:48:21.400 --> 00:48:25.260
of onion or apple, and
you then have religion.

00:48:25.260 --> 00:48:30.360
And then you've crossed over,
in a good way, to the good side.

00:48:30.360 --> 00:48:34.240
And that's when you not only
are willing to cut onions.

00:48:34.240 --> 00:48:36.470
You'll cut onions
for all your friends,

00:48:36.470 --> 00:48:38.100
and you will look
for things to cut.

00:48:38.100 --> 00:48:40.690
When you fall in love
with slicing stuff,

00:48:40.690 --> 00:48:42.024
everything changes.

00:48:42.024 --> 00:48:43.440
And I just had my
knife sharpened,

00:48:43.440 --> 00:48:45.520
so I'm in a really
good mood about this.

00:48:45.520 --> 00:48:47.010
It just brightens your life.

00:48:47.010 --> 00:48:48.782
You go for the small things.

00:48:48.782 --> 00:48:50.240
Enjoy that because
that will really

00:48:50.240 --> 00:48:51.281
change your cooking life.

00:48:51.281 --> 00:48:52.720
I guarantee it.

00:48:52.720 --> 00:48:54.440
AUDIENCE: So always
this time of year,

00:48:54.440 --> 00:48:56.900
when there's just that
first chill in the air,

00:48:56.900 --> 00:48:59.440
I make that lentil soup of
"The Moosewood Cookbook."

00:48:59.440 --> 00:49:01.940
And it warms my heart.

00:49:01.940 --> 00:49:07.130
But from your descriptions, it
sounds like you're constantly

00:49:07.130 --> 00:49:09.170
jumping from recipe
to recipe, or you're

00:49:09.170 --> 00:49:12.610
making a lot of different
things, trying out new things.

00:49:12.610 --> 00:49:15.550
How do you balance between
making something new

00:49:15.550 --> 00:49:18.067
and going back to old favorites?

00:49:18.067 --> 00:49:19.900
MOLLIE KATZEN: That is
such a good question.

00:49:19.900 --> 00:49:22.066
I'm wondering why I've never
been asked that before.

00:49:22.066 --> 00:49:24.380
You're original.

00:49:24.380 --> 00:49:28.180
I test a lot of new
recipes, obviously,

00:49:28.180 --> 00:49:29.900
when I'm working on a cookbook.

00:49:29.900 --> 00:49:33.690
I'm not always
working on a cookbook.

00:49:33.690 --> 00:49:38.420
And in between
cookbook projects--

00:49:38.420 --> 00:49:41.300
which take several years
because those recipes, these,

00:49:41.300 --> 00:49:44.840
I've tested three,
four, or five times

00:49:44.840 --> 00:49:47.650
and actually lose sleep over the
ones I think aren't coming out.

00:49:47.650 --> 00:49:49.600
I really care.

00:49:49.600 --> 00:49:51.350
I really care.

00:49:51.350 --> 00:49:54.710
When I take off my
making a cookbook hat

00:49:54.710 --> 00:49:56.580
and I'm just an
ordinary citizen,

00:49:56.580 --> 00:50:00.110
I am pretty much incapable
of following a recipe.

00:50:00.110 --> 00:50:02.290
I've tried, and it's hard.

00:50:02.290 --> 00:50:03.540
It's a rebellious thing.

00:50:03.540 --> 00:50:05.790
I don't know what it is.

00:50:05.790 --> 00:50:08.840
And I cook very much
by going to the market

00:50:08.840 --> 00:50:14.880
and seeing what's there and what
just speaks to me on that day.

00:50:14.880 --> 00:50:19.725
That said, I do have
a few favorites.

00:50:19.725 --> 00:50:22.020
I can't really follow
even my own recipes,

00:50:22.020 --> 00:50:25.800
but that lentil soup is one that
when I have nothing else going

00:50:25.800 --> 00:50:28.210
on, I just automatically
will put lentils on the stove

00:50:28.210 --> 00:50:30.100
and start making that.

00:50:30.100 --> 00:50:31.350
I cook really simply.

00:50:31.350 --> 00:50:36.500
And it's like being on vacation
to not write things down,

00:50:36.500 --> 00:50:39.080
because a cookbook is
a technical manual.

00:50:39.080 --> 00:50:40.790
It really has to work.

00:50:40.790 --> 00:50:42.630
And also, in writing
one, you don't really

00:50:42.630 --> 00:50:44.840
know exactly whom
you're writing it for.

00:50:44.840 --> 00:50:45.590
What's your habit?

00:50:45.590 --> 00:50:46.450
What's you're habit?

00:50:46.450 --> 00:50:48.110
What do you need me to tell you?

00:50:48.110 --> 00:50:51.230
How comfortable are you filling
in the blanks on your own?

00:50:51.230 --> 00:50:52.920
What does your
kitchen look like?

00:50:52.920 --> 00:50:54.240
What is your attention span?

00:50:54.240 --> 00:50:55.650
What are your taste buds?

00:50:55.650 --> 00:50:57.561
I'm guessing.

00:50:57.561 --> 00:50:59.060
Not to complain,
but it's really fun

00:50:59.060 --> 00:51:01.393
when I'm not having to do
that and when I'm just cooking

00:51:01.393 --> 00:51:02.477
and I don't write it down.

00:51:02.477 --> 00:51:04.268
On the other hand, if
I don't write it down

00:51:04.268 --> 00:51:05.920
and then I really
liked what I made,

00:51:05.920 --> 00:51:07.900
I can't remember what I did.

00:51:07.900 --> 00:51:11.610
But I pretty much don't cook the
same thing more than once ever

00:51:11.610 --> 00:51:13.240
in real life.

00:51:13.240 --> 00:51:15.320
I hope that was not
too disappointing,

00:51:15.320 --> 00:51:17.948
because it's really true.

00:51:17.948 --> 00:51:20.210
DIANA: OK, thank
you so much, Mollie.

00:51:20.210 --> 00:51:21.030
That was awesome.

